<! Weights [2014] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
			
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="weights">
							<header>
								<h2>Weights [2014]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Context</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
										<img src="images/weights_logo.png" height="200" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 5% 5%; border-radius:0px;"/>
								</p>
								Weights App was created to fulfil a very simple purpose: to end the neglect of the weights at the Gym.<br>   
								The idea was to make it a great and versatile tool for both the weight machines but also the cardio exercises.<br>  
								To do this, the application had to include the following features:<br><br>
								<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 Logging of different gym exercises;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Support for both the weight & the cardio machines;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Keeping track of the exercises evolution;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Registration of the performance evolution;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Flexibility to change/edit the logs;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Integration of the Google Material Design (similarly to Horarios Vimeca);</li>
								</ul></ul>												

								Besides these features, the application had to be simple, easy-to-use and provide the core functions within very clicks, in order to make it useable for gym environments.<br><br>

								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/weights.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/weights.png" height="600" style="float:center; margin: 0 0% 0% 5%; border-radius:0px;"/>
									</a>							
								</p>
								
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Implementation</strong></li>
								</ul>
								As pictured above, Weighs App contained different menus for the different features, all accessible from a unique sidebar:<br><br>
								<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>The List</b>:</li>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Main door(menu) of the App;</li>
												<li>&#9632 List to record all the activities (entries);</li>
												<li>&#9632 Allows entering a machine or a cardio exercise;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Contains the Name, Machine ID and Latest Log of the entry;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Allows list sorting for each of the fields;</li>												
												<li>&#9632 Allows edition of every entry;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Supports a brief description for each entry;</li>
											</ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>myEvolution</b>:</li>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Contains a graph with the stats for every entry;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Plots a Weight/Repetitions/Series graph for the machines;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Plots a Distance/Duration/Level graph for the cardio;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Allows list sorting for Name and ID;</li>
											</ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>myWeight</b>:</li>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Logs the weight values;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Plots the weight evolution;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Records the log entries details;</li>
											</ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Examples</b>:</li>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Not yet implemented;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Will contain a set of predefined exercises;</li>
											</ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Remove</b>:</li><ul>
												<li>&#9632 Simple interface to remove deprecated exercises;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Support removal of one or many entries at a time;</li>
											</ul>
									</ul></ul>
								
								Besides the features above, there is also a settings menu to allow the user to change between imperial (Pounds & Miles) and metric (Kilometers & Kilograms) units.<br>
								To check the App, click on the icon below.<br><br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="http://goo.gl/0n9pib" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;">
										<img src="images/google.png" id="googleLink" width="300"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								
								
							</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>
					
<! Horarios Vimeca II [2014] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">

					<div id="horarios_vimeca_ii">
							<header>
								<h2>Horarios Vimeca II [2014]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Time to Renew</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
										<img src="images/vimeca_v2.png" height="200" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 5% 5%; border-radius:0px;"/>
								</p>
								Ever since Horarios Vimeca first version was released, it had been downloaded over 1700 times, having more than 600 active installations.<br>
								The App had good reviews, for it was fulfilling it's purpose without major flourishes.<br>
								Nevertheless the number of active users of the application had stop increased for a while, and there where some problems and complaints.<br>
								Amongst them:<br><br>								
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 A few timetables stopped working;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Some routes couldn't be loaded;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Advertising banner was unwelcome;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Some summer/winter timetables where switched;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Application would sometimes block;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Data loading was very was slow;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Users couldn't access the data offline;</li>
										<li>&#9658 There was no option to save a favourites list;</li>
									</ul></ul>			
								
								Furthermore, with the release of Android version 5.0 and the Material Design, the appearance became rather old fashioned.<br>
								Regarding this, the Google Material Design guidelines <a href="http://www.google.com/design/spec/material-design/introduction.html" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">(click here for more info)</a>, were very handy, since they brought a standardized form for a simple, nice and clean interface.<br><br>

								<p style="text-align:centre;">
								<a href="images/vimeca_v2_2b.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/vimeca_v2_2.png" height="600" style="float:center; margin: 0 0% 0% 5%; border-radius:0px;"/>
								</a>
								</p>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Restyling</strong></li>
								</ul>

								The new Horarios Vimeca application, pictured above, touched three different points:<br><br>
								
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 Correction of bugs, reported on the previous version;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Introduction of a new look & feel, compatible with the latest Google guidelines;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Introduction of new features, to enhance the App potential;</li>
									</ul></ul>			
								
								Starting with the design, the purpose was to achieve:<br><br>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 Cleaner/simpler interface, respecting the new graphical guidelines;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Backwards compatibility to older Android versions;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Brand new logo, in line with the Material Design;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Faster loading of information;</li>
										<li>&#9658 One menu to access all the features;</li>
									</ul></ul>			
								
								Interlinked with the new design, the added main features where the following:<br><br>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 Favourites menu, for both routes and timetables;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Institutional information menu, with Vimeca information/contacts;</li>  	
										<li>&#9658 Access to saved data offline;</li>
									</ul></ul>			

								<b>UPDATE:</b> about six months after the release of this new version, the results were clear: about 30% more active users (above 850).<br>
								Also, the number of total installs jumped from about 1700 to more than 2200, and the cumulative average rating also increased.<br><br>
								
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="http://goo.gl/Fylpam" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;">
										<img src="images/google.png" id="googleLink" width="300"/>
									</a>
								</p>
							</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>
					
				
<! Meteo Station [2013] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="meteo_station">
							<header>
								<h2>Meteo Station [2013]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Basics</strong></li>
								</ul>
									The idea: to build a homemade Meteorological Station.<br>
									Why: to practice the Python scripting.<br>
									How: using the versatile Raspberry Pi (which was already introduced <a href="#RPi">here</a>).<br>
									To go along with the Raspberry, I chose: a temperature sensor, a couple of PIC16F819, two matched RF Transceivers and a breadboard.
									With these components I started the project: to create a Meteorological Station (or, a "basic digital thermometer").<br>
									Below I explain the project in further detail, in 3 parts: the <b>Reading Station</b>; the <b>Link to the Internet</b>; and the <b>Displaying Website</b>.
								<br><br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Reading Station</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/pic16f.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/pic16f.jpg" height="400" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
									This 1st part of the system, where the temperature is sensed, is a standalone module powered by a battery and so, completely portable (up to a certain radius distance from the Raspberry Pi).<br>
									The main components are:<br><br>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b> 
											<a href="http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/data_sheets/TMP35_36_37.pdf" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">TMP37:</a></b> 
											a simple low voltage temperature sensor from <a href="http://www.analog.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Analog</a>. 
											This sensor is intended for applications over the range of 5 C to 100 C and provides an output scale factor of 20 mV/C.
										</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>
											<a href="http://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/DeviceDoc/39598F.pdf" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">PIC16F189:</a></b> 
											a generic purpose Microcontroller from <a href="http://www.microchip.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Microchip</a>, with the essential features (for this project) of Analog-to-Digital conversion and UART interfacing; 
										</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>
											<a href="http://www.sureelectronics.net/goods.php?id=1053" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Wireless RF Transceiver:</a></b> 
											a 2 pieces RF Transceiver with an UART interface, for establishing the communication between the serial interfaces of the PIC16F819 and the Raspberry Pi.</b>
										</li>					
									</ul></ul>
									The configuration setup is very simple: a simple C program is loaded into the PIC, to read the TMP37 output voltage with the internal ADC.
									This program is then responsible to send the raw information (hexadecimal format from 0x00 to 0xFF) through the serial interface into the PIC RF module which forwards it to its twin module, on the Raspberry side.<br><br>
								
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Link to the Internet</strong></li>
								</ul>
									The information emitted above is then received by the Raspberry Pi, using its RF Module connected to the serial interface.
									A Python script transforms the hexadecimal information gathered into both Voltage and Temperature using the formulas:<br><br>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Voltage</b> = Raw/255 * 5 V;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Temperature</b> = Voltage * 50 C;</li>
									</ul></ul>
																		
									The reason to process the information at this side of the link instead of the PIC's side, is to simplify the information transmission (only the raw signal is sent). 
									Furthermore the purpose of the whole project was to improve the Python scripting skills, and not the C programming.<br>
									Having the information on the Raspberry side, the python script is then responsible to upload it to an SQL server online.
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rasp_rf.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/rasp_rf.jpg" width="400" style="margin: 4% 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Displaying Website</strong></li>
								</ul>
									Here a php script running on a webserver, accesses the same SQL database that is linked to the Raspberry, and downloads the latest temperature.
									This value is then printed on the display inside a circle which has different colours for distinct temperatures:
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b style="color: blue;">Blue:</b> temperature is less than 10 C;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b style="color: green;">Green:</b> temperature is in between 10 C and 20 C;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b style="color: orange;">Orange:</b> temperature is in between 20 C and 30 C;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b style="color: red;">Red:</b> temperature is higher than 30 C;</li>
									</ul></ul>			
									The aforementioned website, which is public and available at <a href="http://meteo.comuv.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;">http://meteo.comuv.com/</a> is quite straightforward and effective in filling its only purpose (for now at least): showing the current temperature of the room where the Reading Station is located at.
									A picture is found below.
								</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/meteo_web.png" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/meteo_web.png" width="500" style="float:center; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>To be Continued</strong></li>
								</ul>
									The first part of the project was finished with success, but further improvements are lacking:
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Specific voltage reference:</b> for improving the measurements accuracy;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Some batteries:</b> replacing the USB power connection will improve the system versatility;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>More/Different sensors:</b> carbon monoxide gas sensor, gas sensor, relative humidity sensor, e.g.;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>New PCB:</b> instead of a breadboard, the final system should be embedded on a PCB;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Custom Case:</b> for a final product look, a case ought be made to protect the whole system.</li>
									</ul></ul>	
									UPDATE: the site is still online, but the Meteo Station is currently not working.
									<br>	
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

				
					
				
<! eMenu Service I [2013] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">

					<div id="emenu_service">
