<! Raspberry Experiences [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="raspberry_experiences">
							<header>
								<h2>Raspberry Experiences [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_1.jpg" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_1.jpg" height="250"  style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>	
									<li><strong>Raspwho?</strong></li>
								</ul>


								The Raspberry Pi is a small computer developed for teaching purposes but whose potential has facilitated its deployment as a very powerful tool for both homemade projects and even some companies.
								The possibility to have a computer for $40, running a Linux OS, connected to the internet, and having directly available for example an UART, an I2C module or a dozen of GPIO pins, is very attractive.<br><br>
								<ul>
								<li><strong>SSH Remote Control</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>One of the first thing I made was registering a dynamic DNS service, so I could gain remote access to the Raspberry (connected to the web via the Ethernet port). Having done this I also enabled on my router the NAT service, where I mapped the SSH Port of my $40 computer to a public Port. This way I became capable to enter the device&#8217;s terminal from any place of the web, and thus configure it. Even though an LCD could be connected via HDMI port, as well as a keyboard and a mouse turning this low-cost PC into a &#8220;normal&#8221; computer, I&#8217;ve chosen to access it from my PC with SSH, allowing a more comfortable operation.</p>
								<ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_2.jpg" height="200" style="float:left; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<li><strong>FTP Server</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>As a second step, I configured an FTP server running as a daemon, and then plugged an  USB Flash Drive on the Raspberry Pi, so I could share files between all the computers on my network, and store them on only one location. Furthermore I mapped both FTP Ports on the router with NAT, and so I gained access to these files from any remote place. In a near future I&#8217;m considering replacing the USB Flash Drive with an 1 TB HD Drive using a Hub (since it draws a lot of current), thus creating a spot on the network where I can access all my data.</p>
								<ul>
								<li><strong>Transmission Remote<br /></strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>Another configuration I made, towards a more integrated/practical IT environment, was configuring a Torrent client (namely Transmission), running as daemon, associated to the corresponding  remote access service. Then I added a remote transmission widget on my browser, and opened the ports on the router, et voilà, I was now able to add/remove/manage any legal torrent/magnet from any place, with the great commodity of arriving home with the contents already downloaded and available for use.</p>
								<ul>
								<li><strong>Receipt Management Software</strong></li>
								</ul>
								Although the utility of all the previous configurations, the most interesting thing I made so far with the Raspberry Pi was to develop a simple C routine to run on the raspberry or any device accessing with an SSH session.<br>
								This consisted in a Receipt Management SW, where I could save, add, list or organize different receipts very easily, instead of using an ordinary receipt book. This program which would run by simply executing a bin file on the Raspberry Pi terminal, had the information saved in the USB Flash Drive so it could be easy to transport and hard get lost.<br>
								As of the program itself, it had the following interface:<br><br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_4.png" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_4.png" height="280"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>Here, if you selected the 2nd option, for instance, you would have a list of the available plates, and then the details of the specified one:</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_5.png" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_5.png" height="310"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>
								<li><strong>General Overview</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>At the end of these experiences a lot of advantages of this &#8220;cheap&#8221; computer seem obvious: it can perform most of  the same operations as an ordinary computer, while consuming much less resources, it&#8217;s very light and portable, provides very easy access to low-level components  it can be easily remotely accessed (with a smartphone inclusively).</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio"  class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

<! Micro-Mouse II [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">

					<div id="micro_mouse_ii">
							<header>
								<h2>Micro-Mouse II [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								
								<a href="images/rato0.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato0.jpg" height="200" style="float:right; margin: 5% 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Motivation</strong></li>
								</ul>
									As a second attempt on the Micro-Mouse competition title, after achieving the 2nd place in the previous year (<a href="#MicroMouse" class="link">Micro-Mouse 2011</a>),
								me and <a title="Fábio Rico's Website" class="link" href="http://www.fabiorvrico.wordpress.com" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;">Fábio Rico</a>, decided to participate again.<br>
									This time, however, a decision was made to build the entire robot from scratch, and then add some intelligence to it, which made the task harder, but also much more amusing and challenging.<br> 
									An early sketch can be found on the picture to the right.<br>
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Development</strong></li>
								</ul>
									We started out with the idea: "Let's create a tank-like robot!".<br> 
									We assembled some bicycle chains (to create robot caterpillar tracks), a thin base of metal for the structure, pieces of wood to fasten the sensors and create some wheels, acrylic for the Lighthouse receiver pole and then we bought all the electronics required and got down to work.<br>
								<a href="images/rato3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato3.jpg" height="250" style="float:left; margin: 2% 5% 1% 1%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
									A servo was connected to the beacon receiver, allowing a 180 degrees movement, for an increased probability of capturing the signal.<br>
									Some of the electronics used:<br><br>
								<ul>
									<ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 1* Ground Sensors: <a href="http://www.vishay.com/docs/83760/tcrt5000.pdf" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">TCRT5000</a> from <a href="http://www.vishay.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Vishay</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* Obstacle Sensor: <a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/datasheets/Components/GP2Y0A21YK.pdf" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">GP2Y0A21YK</a> from <a href="http://sharp-world.com/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Sharp</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 1* Infrared Receiver: <a href="http://www.farnell.com/datasheets/9749.pdf" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">HIM602</a> from <a href="http://www.apc-hero.co.uk/" onclick="window.open(this.href);return false;" class="link">Hero</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* DC Motors: 12V with 20RPM;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* Servo Motors: TBD;</li>
									</ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul>
								</ul>
								</p>
								<br><br><br>Regarding the developed board, pictured above, it contains:<br><br>
								<a href="images/rato2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato2.jpg" height="250" style="float:right; margin: 0 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>	
								<ul>
									<ul>
										<li>&#9658 Hot-pluggable socket for the pic32 development board;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Signal conditioning for the all the DC motors, servos and sensors provided on-board;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Some on-board buttons and LEDs available for testing;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Hot-pluggable slot for an RF UART module provided, for remote control of the vehicle (non-competition add-on);</li>
										<li>&#9658 Output/input ports available for future usage as a generic tests board.</li>
									</ul>
								</ul>
									Regarding the SW, most of the previous year robot intelligence was re-utilized, however many aspects had to be optimized/modified or completely renovated due to the new hardware.<br>
									The final robot, dressed for the competition is pictured to the right, on its full splendour as a small tank-like vehicle!<br><br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Competition</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									After the robot was assembled the tests sessions began. One of these sessions can be seen in the video below, where the robot had to avoid the obstacles around it, whilst not having a destination reference.
								</p>
								<br>
								<span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:centre; display: block;'>
									<iframe width='100%' height='500' src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/D5OZdfUp0_E" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
								</span>
								<br>
												
									Although in latter training sessions, and in the competition training grounds the robot had a great performance, there where some problems during the competition itself.<br>
								There was a problem with the ground sensors (used for beacon area detection): they were receiving the signals emitted from the contestant's obstacle detectors, and interpreting that as an indication of "arrival at destination". 
								That meant a faulty behaviour, immediately after the start of the competition, and consequent declassification from the match.
								During the second round of the competition, efforts were made to solve this problem, but with no success.<br>
								In the end the robot was declassified, but still, it was a great experience.<br><br>
								
