<! Illumination No-Cost [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="illumination_no_cost">
							<header>
								<h2>Illumination No-Cost [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>					
								<a href="images/rf_1.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
									<img src="images/rf_1.png" height="300" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
								<li><strong>The "What?"</strong></li>
								</ul>
								This project is related with the work I made for my master thesis, and involves the concept of Energy Harvesting and the means to transform the received energy into a useful application.<br>
								This work was made in cooperation with the Telecommunications Institute of Aveiro, under the orientation of Professor Dr. Nuno Borges Carvalho, to whom I&#8217;m grateful for the support provided.<br>
								Basically the idea here was, through the understanding of the non-linear processes involved in the rectification process that converts the ambient RF power into DC energy, creating systems with high efficiency and/or output voltage. This ought to be achieved from the waves emitted by an ordinary FM emitter antenna, allowing the powering of 2/3 low consumption LED&#8217;s from a couple of hundred meters of distance to the source.<br>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>The "How?"</strong></li>
								</ul>

								<p>Since the maximum harvested energy from the receiver antenna is always limited, and it's very hard to increase at about 100 MHz specially (only developing agglomerates or very large or  of antennas) a very delicate design of the circuit that effectively converts the RF energy from the waves into the DC is required. So it was the main point of this work to develop methods for increasing the efficiency of this process. A special focus was given to the matching of the conversion circuit, since a careful analysis revealed that the reflected power consisted in the major percentage of the power loss.</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rf_2.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_2.png" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" width="474" height="294" />
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>That said, without entering an extensive level of detail, one of the main tools developed was a software running on ADS 2012, that allowing a flexible and accurate matching of the circuit. This tool allowed to match the circuit considering either for a specific output voltage or for a higher power efficiency. A picture of this can be found above, where it&#8217;s seen the smith charts used for the matching on both purposes (power efficiency and output voltage) on the centre and a series of auxiliary equations on the side. Also the results for each of the matching circles (and in the limit the red point), show the current values for those positions.<br />
								Applying this theory a couple of circuits were developed, some to achieve higher efficiency using only one diode as main rectifier, and other employed more complex rectifiers/voltage multipliers such as the Dickson or the Villard to attain output voltages as high as possible. In parallel a simple FM antenna was built for proof of concept purposes. Some of the circuits developed can be found on the pictures below.</p>
 								<p style="text-align:centre;">
 									<a href="images/rf_3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_3.jpg" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" height="180"  />
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>The "Big Picture"</strong></li>
								</ul>
								Getting all the elements together, a system that effectively converted the energy of a FM radio emitter into visible light was achieved, having been tested on the field in Aveiro, Portugal.<br>
								Basically the experienced consisted in two phases:<br><br>
								<ul>
									<ul>
										<li><span style="line-height:13px;"><strong>a)</strong> The energy-harvesting circuits without LED&#8217;s were connected to the FM antenna on one side, and to a multimeter on the other to measure the harvested DC voltage.</span></li>
										<li><strong>b) </strong>The multimeter and the previous circuits were replaced with a different set of circuits with 1 or 2 LED&#8217;s, to verify if the harvested energy could generate light.</li>
									</ul>
								</ul>
								<p>Both these experiences are briefly presented on a short video, presented below, where an overview of the practical results of this work can be found</p>
								<span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:centre; display: block;'>
									<iframe class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='593' height='364' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/xEHFZO_CSiU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0'></iframe>
								</span>
								<br>
								<p>On the picture below , the best results achieved are again presented, where it can be seen that up to a distance of 400m from an emitter, 2 LEDs where successfully powered up, having been obtained about 5.34 V.</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rf_4.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_4.png" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" height="350px">								
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>Closer to the same antenna, with both LEDs also turned on, a voltage as high as 7.01 V was possible.</p>
								
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly" >Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

<! Micro-Mouse I [2011] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">
					<div id="micro_mouse_i">
							<header>
								<h2>Micro-Mouse I [2011]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro1.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro1.jpg" style="float:left; margin: 1% 5% 1% 1%; border-radius:10px;"width="400">
									</a>
								</p>
								Micro-Mouse is an event where small robots compete against each other to solve maze as fastest and with the minimum collisions as possible.<br>
								Basically the robots have to follow a signal until they reach a destination, and then they have to return to their starting point, and all has to be made without any human interference.<br>
								Although this was a multidisciplinary contest evolving both Hardware and Software, it was chosen to borrow the hardware provided by the organization of the event and focus on the software to solve the maze, only.<br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro2.jpg"  style="float:right; margin: 1% 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;" width="200">
									</a>
								</p>
								This robot, that came equipped with two DC motors and respective H-bridges, three Sharp distance sensors, an IV receiver (to detect the signal emitted from the centre of the maze) and a pic18f for processing, had to combine the abilities of following walls, avoiding other robots and finding the centre of the maze, all on it's own.<br>
								The developed algorithm had to:<br><br>
								<ul>
									<li>&#9658 Follow Walls</li>
									<li>&#9658 Avoid Obstacles (Other robots, very near walls)</li>
									<li>&#9658 Follow Beacon (to reach the centre)</li>
									<li>&#9658 Avoid Beacon (after reaching the centre of the maze, the implemented solution to reach the starting point was to just get away from the centre for a specified amount of time and then stopping)</li>
								</ul>
								The developed code, which was compiled with CCS and then sent to a pic18f258 trough a TinyBootLoader application, followed a simple structure with functions for each of the operations it had to execute, and some interruptions to generate time-triggered events, and some reads from the ADC.<br><br>
								The robot itself, which is shown in the photo to the right, having made a very good contest on the first three rounds, applied to the finals where it managed the second place of the competition, what earned us a pic32 proprietary board from the University of Aveiro Electronics Department (picture below).<br><br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro3.jpg" style="border-radius:10px" width="500">
									</a>
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio"  class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>
					
